21.text: Homepage Draft in Sijuade Oguntayo Saved Publish Turn Your Browser into a Smart Semantic Search Engine Build your own private, lightning-fast web knowledge index with Chrome, FastAPI, FAISS, and Ollama Type caption for image (optional) Introduction Have you ever wasted time digging through your browser’s history or scrolling endlessly through bookmarks just to find that one critical insight you once came across?

22.text: We’ve all been there: desperately recalling keywords, guessing titles, or struggling to retrace steps to a crucial blog post or documentation snippet. What if your browser could remember not just the pages you’ve visited, but precisely what mattered most about them? In this guide, I’ll show you how I transformed my Chrome browser into a private, fast semantic search engine.

23.text: Powered entirely by local technologies — Chrome, FastAPI, Ollama, and FAISS — my setup remembers every meaningful snippet from my browsing history and retrieves it instantly using natural-language questions. Imagine never again having to recall exact keywords or manually manage bookmarks. Instead, effortlessly ask your browser questions like, “Where did I read about async data loading in React?” or “Show me that blog post on vector search.

24.text: ” Moments later, you’re staring at precisely highlighted passages — no guesswork, no hassle, just clarity. Let’s dive into exactly how to build this powerful, privacy-first browsing tool yourself. Motivation Every day, we sift through mountains of online information — articles, tutorials, blogs, documentation. Yet when we need to revisit an idea or recall an insight, our browsers let us down. Bookmarks quickly become cluttered, neglected, or entirely forgotten.

25.text: Keyword searches are limited to the exact phrases we remember, not the underlying concepts we care about. Browser history itself offers nothing more than a list of visited URLs, devoid of context or significance. The result? wasted time — precious minutes spent retracing digital footsteps rather than solving real-world problems. But what if our browsers could truly understand what we’ve read? What if they remembered the meaning behind each page visited, rather than just raw text?

26.text: By combining Chrome with locally-hosted semantic embedding (via Ollama’s powerful mxbai-embed-large model) and blazing-fast indexing through FAISS, I created a browsing experience that goes far beyond bookmarks or keyword search. Now, when I ask, “where did I read about AI and the future of work?” , I’m instantly provided with the exact snippet I need, highlighted right on the page — transforming hours of tedious searching into mere seconds of effortless retrieval.

27.text: In the sections ahead, I’ll walk you step-by-step through building your own private, local semantic browsing powerhouse — because your time should be spent gaining insights, not chasing them down. Architecture Overview Type caption for image (optional) To build your browser-based semantic search engine, you’ll bring together three powerful yet simple-to-integrate components: a Chrome extension, a FastAPI backend paired with Ollama embeddings, and a FAISS vector index.

28.text: Here’s how it all seamlessly fits together: Content Extraction (Chrome Extension) A lightweight JavaScript content script (content.js) runs silently on every visited page. It intelligently strips away irrelevant content — scripts, navigation elements, hidden or invisible text — to capture a clean, meaningful snapshot of page content. Relevant metadata (URL, title, timestamp) is collected alongside this cleaned text.

29.text: Embedding & Indexing (FastAPI + Ollama + FAISS) The Chrome extension forwards the cleaned text chunks to your local FastAPI backend. FastAPI routes these chunks into a locally-hosted Ollama instance running the high-performance mxbai-embed-large embedding model, rapidly transforming text into semantic embeddings. Generated embeddings are stored directly into a FAISS index — built for blazing-fast semantic similarity searches.

30.text: Lightweight metadata (URLs, titles, timestamps) is locally cached in Chrome’s storage for easy management and retrieval. Semantic Query & Highlight (Popup + Highlight Script) Enter a natural-language query (e.g., “Show me the article about vector search” ). FastAPI rapidly queries the FAISS index, returning top semantic matches. Clicking on a result opens the original webpage and precisely highlights the relevant text — instantly reconnecting you to the original context.

31.text: This modular architecture keeps every step — data extraction, embedding, indexing, querying, and highlighting — completely local on your device. As a result, you get unmatched speed, uncompromised privacy, and a deeply intuitive browsing experience. Key Implementation Details Let’s dive into some aspects of turning this powerful concept into reality, complete with actionable code snippets.

32.text: Capturing the Web Without Noise To ensure accurate semantic search, you first need to reliably extract meaningful content: A Chrome content script (content.js) clones the page’s DOM. It filters out unnecessary noise — scripts, navigation menus, footers, and hidden elements — using predefined exclusion rules. Only visible and meaningful text nodes remain, resulting in clean text data.

33.text: Perfectly Sized Embeddings (Chunking & Vectorizing) To maintain meaningful context within model constraints: Text is segmented into semantic chunks based on sentence boundaries, carefully balancing context and embedding model window limits (approximately 300 tokens per 500 characters). Fast Semantic Recall (FAISS Indexing & Search) FastAPI serves as your semantic search orchestrator: Text chunks become embeddings via Ollama’s local mxbai-embed-large model.

Instant Highlights When viewing results: Clicking a result injects JavaScript directly onto the target page, precisely highlighting your retrieved snippet.

36.text: It gracefully handles exact and fuzzy text matches, ensuring robust highlights even on dynamic or responsive web pages. Keeping It Local (Why It Matters) Running your entire semantic browsing engine locally might seem unconventional — but it comes with powerful advantages: Absolute Privacy: Your browsing data, content embeddings, and search queries never leave your device. No third-party can track or analyze your insights.

37.text: Instant Performance: By hosting the Ollama embedding model and FAISS index locally, semantic searches execute at fast speeds. Uninterrupted Offline Access: Once your pages are indexed, semantic queries continue to work seamlessly, even without an internet connection. Cost Efficiency & Control: Forget API rate limits, subscription fees, or surprise charges. Your only investment is your own hardware.

38.text: Running a minimal stack — Chrome, FastAPI, Ollama, and FAISS — right on your own machine ensures your browsing history becomes a personal, powerful, and completely private semantic knowledge base. Lessons Learned Here’s what I discovered while transforming my browser into a semantic powerhouse: Surprisingly Easy: Ollama Setting up Ollama locally to run mxbai-embed-large embeddings on CPU was astonishingly smooth. Embeddings were generated in milliseconds.

39.text: Surprisingly Challenging: Reliable On-Page Highlights Implementing accurate highlighting was unexpectedly tough. Exact text matches required heavy text normalization and regex-escaping, yet dynamic page layouts or content reflows regularly broke highlights. Experiments with tracking chunk positions using character offsets were derailed by responsive designs.. What I’d Improve Next Time Smarter Semantic Chunking: Simple sentence-splitting works but leaves room for improvement.

40.text: In the next iteration, I plan to explore: Topic-driven segmentation , clustering semantically related sentences. Overlapping sliding windows , preserving better context at chunk boundaries. Adaptive chunk sizing , based on embedding token counts instead of fixed character limits. Final Thoughts Instead of wasting time on endless bookmark searches or vague keyword guessing, I now effortlessly reconnect with key insights in seconds.

41.text: With just a few hundred lines of intuitive code — and leveraging Chrome, FastAPI, Ollama, and FAISS — I’ve built a solution that’s fully local, fast, and privacy-first. Check out the full source code here on GitHub , give it a spin, and feel free to open an issue or drop a comment — I’d love to hear your feedback, insights, and suggestions for improvements.

42.text: Embedding models April 8, 2024 Ollama supports embedding models, making it possible to build retrieval augmented generation (RAG) applications that combine text prompts with existing documents or other data. What are embedding models?

43.text: Embedding models are models that are trained specifically to generate vector embeddings : long arrays of numbers that represent semantic meaning for a given sequence of text: The resulting vector embedding arrays can then be stored in a database, which will compare them as a way to search for data that is similar in meaning.

44.text: Example embedding models Model Parameter Size mxbai-embed-large 334M View model nomic-embed-text 137M View model all-minilm 23M View model Usage To generate vector embeddings, first pull a model: ollama pull mxbai-embed-large Next, use the REST API , Python or JavaScript libraries to generate vector embeddings from the model: REST API curl http://localhost:11434/api/embed -d '{ "model": "mxbai-embed-large", "input": "Llamas are members of the camelid family" }' Python library ollama.

45.text: embed( model='mxbai-embed-large', input='Llamas are members of the camelid family', ) Javascript library ollama.embed({ model: 'mxbai-embed-large', input: 'Llamas are members of the camelid family', }) Ollama also integrates with popular tooling to support embeddings workflows such as LangChain and LlamaIndex . Example This example walks through building a retrieval augmented generation (RAG) application using Ollama and embedding models.

46.text: Step 1: Generate embeddings pip install ollama chromadb Create a file named example.

47.text: py with the contents: import ollama import chromadb documents = [ "Llamas are members of the camelid family meaning they're pretty closely related to vicuñas and camels", "Llamas were first domesticated and used as pack animals 4,000 to 5,000 years ago in the Peruvian highlands", "Llamas can grow as much as 6 feet tall though the average llama between 5 feet 6 inches and 5 feet 9 inches tall", "Llamas weigh between 280 and 450 pounds and can carry 25 to 30 percent of their body weight", "Llamas are vegetarians and have very efficient digestive systems", "Llamas live to be about 20 years old, though some only live for 15 years and others live to be 30 years old", ] client = chromadb.

48.text: Client() collection = client.create_collection(name="docs") # store each document in a vector embedding database for i, d in enumerate(documents): response = ollama.embed(model="mxbai-embed-large", input=d) embeddings = response["embeddings"] collection.add( ids=[str(i)], embeddings=embeddings, documents=[d] ) Step 2: Retrieve Next, add the code to retrieve the most relevant document given an example prompt: # an example input input = "What animals are llamas related to?

49.text: " # generate an embedding for the input and retrieve the most relevant doc response = ollama.embed( model="mxbai-embed-large", input=prompt ) results = collection.query( query_embeddings=[response["embeddings"]], n_results=1 ) data = results['documents'][0][0] Step 3: Generate Lastly, use the prompt and the document retrieved in the previous step to generate an answer! # generate a response combining the prompt and data we retrieved in step 2 output = ollama.

50.text: generate( model="llama2", prompt=f"Using this data: {data}. Respond to this prompt: {input}" ) print(output['response']) Then, run the code: python example.py Llama 2 will answer the prompt What animals are llamas related to? using the data: Llamas are members of the camelid family, which means they are closely related to two other animals: vicuñas and camels.

51.text: All three species belong to the same evolutionary lineage and share many similarities in terms of their physical characteristics, behavior, and genetic makeup. Specifically, llamas are most closely related to vicuñas, with which they share a common ancestor that lived around 20-30 million years ago. Both llamas and vicuñas are members of the family Camelidae, while camels belong to a different family (Dromedary).
